AI Global Trade Platform - Final Report

Introduction

  • This project analyzes U.S. and international trade data, focusing on Ohios export trends and socioeconomic factors across U.S. states. Using data from the U.S. Census, UN Comtrade, and OECD, the goal is to uncover insights that can support AI-driven trade strategies. This report summarizes key findings and suggests ideas for applying AI and data analytics to real-world trade challenges.

Data Sources

  • U.S. Census Bureau APIs.
  • UN Comtrade Database
  • OECD Data Explorer

Key Insights:

  • Population is not a reliable indicator of market wealth. Our analysis shows no strong correlation between a states population and its median household income. Instead, factors like higher education and low poverty rates are much stronger predictors of economic health.

  • Ohios export landscape is shifting. While traditional sectors like vehicles and electronics saw a decline, high-value, specialized industries such as aerospace and defense parts showed significant growth, pointing to a strategic opportunity.

  • Global trade is dominated by a few key players. The USA and China are the worlds largest importers by a significant margin. For U.S. exporters, machinery and electrical equipment remain the most valuable sectors, with China being a primary market.

Observation:

  • Maryland, DC, and Massachusetts stand out with the highest median incomes, all above $85,000.

  • Puerto Rico has the lowest income by far, under $25,000.

  • Mississippi, West Virginia, and Arkansas are among the lowest U.S. states, with incomes below $50,000.

  • Most northeastern and west coast states show higher incomes, while southern states tend to have lower incomes.

  • Population size is not a predictor of economic prosperity at the state level.

  • No Strong Correlation: This means that having more people doesnt automatically make a state wealthier on average.

1) Calculating Socioeconomic Rates and Displaying as a Table by State
merged <- merged %>%
  mutate(
    edu_rate      = edu_count      / edu_pop_25plus,  # % with bachelors degree
    unemp_rate    = unemp_count    / labor_force_pop, # % unemployed
    poverty_rate  = poverty_count  / poverty_pop,     # % in poverty
    industry_rate = industry_count / employed_pop     # % in manufacturing
  )

table_data <- merged %>%
  select(NAME, edu_rate, unemp_rate, poverty_rate, industry_rate)

Compute Predictions
# Fit both models on training data
full_model <- lm(median_income ~ value + edu_rate + unemp_rate + poverty_rate + industry_rate, data = train_data)
reduced_model <- lm(median_income ~ edu_rate + poverty_rate, data = train_data)

# Predict on test set
full_pred <- predict(full_model, newdata = test_data)
reduced_pred <- predict(reduced_model, newdata = test_data)

# Compute RMSE
rmse <- function(actual, predicted) sqrt(mean((actual - predicted)^2, na.rm = TRUE))
# Compute R-squared for predictions
rsq <- function(actual, predicted) 1 - sum((actual - predicted)^2) / sum((actual - mean(actual))^2)

# Full model metrics
full_model_rmse <- rmse(test_data$median_income, full_pred)
full_model_rsq <- rsq(test_data$median_income, full_pred)

# Reduced model metrics
reduced_model_rmse <- rmse(test_data$median_income, reduced_pred)
reduced_model_rsq <- rsq(test_data$median_income, reduced_pred)

# Print results
cat("Full model RMSE:   ", round(full_model_rmse, 2), "\n")
## Full model RMSE:    8678.85
cat("Full model R square:     ", round(full_model_rsq, 3), "\n")
## Full model R square:      0.76
cat("Reduced model RMSE:", round(reduced_model_rmse, 2), "\n")
## Reduced model RMSE: 17603.37
cat("Reduced model R square:  ", round(reduced_model_rsq, 3), "\n")
## Reduced model R square:   0.011

Interpretation

Full Model

  • RMSE: 8,678.85 On average, predictions are off by about $8,679.
  • R: 0.76 The model explains 76% of the variation in median income on the test set.

Reduced Model:

  • RMSE: 17,603.37 Much higher error; predictions are off by around $17,603 on average.
  • R: 0.011 The model explains almost nothing (just 1%) of the variation in the test set.

Observation

  • The full model performs much better than the reduced model on the test data.
  • The reduced model is too simple and does not generalize well.
  • Even though some variables werent statistically significant, the full model predicts more accurately and should be preferred.

This observation highlights information for developing the AI Global Trade Platform

  • Multifactor Insights: Including multiple features (even those not individually significant) captures the complexity of economic and trade dynamics. This approach helps the platform uncover deeper patterns, identify export opportunities, and assess risks more effectively.

# Aggregate imports by Commodity, Category, and Month
imports_aug2024_agg <- imports_aug2024 %>%
  select(Commodity = I_COMMODITY_SDESC, Category, Import_Value = GEN_VAL_MO) %>%
  mutate(Month = "Aug2024") %>%
  group_by(Commodity, Category, Month) %>%
  summarise(Import_Value = sum(Import_Value, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

imports_may2025_agg <- imports_may2025 %>%
  select(Commodity = I_COMMODITY_SDESC, Category, Import_Value = GEN_VAL_MO) %>%
  mutate(Month = "May2025") %>%
  group_by(Commodity, Category, Month) %>%
  summarise(Import_Value = sum(Import_Value, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

# Aggregate exports similarly
exports_aug2024_agg <- exports_aug2024 %>%
  select(Commodity = E_COMMODITY_SDESC, Category, Export_Value = ALL_VAL_MO) %>%
  mutate(Month = "Aug2024") %>%
  group_by(Commodity, Category, Month) %>%
  summarise(Export_Value = sum(Export_Value, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

exports_may2025_agg <- exports_may2025 %>%
  select(Commodity = E_COMMODITY_SDESC, Category, Export_Value = ALL_VAL_MO) %>%
  mutate(Month = "May2025") %>%
  group_by(Commodity, Category, Month) %>%
  summarise(Export_Value = sum(Export_Value, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")
2. Join Import and Export Data by Commodity for Each Month
aug_2024 <- full_join(exports_aug2024_agg, imports_aug2024_agg, by = c("Commodity", "Category", "Month"))
may_2025 <- full_join(exports_may2025_agg, imports_may2025_agg, by = c("Commodity", "Category", "Month"))

combined_data <- bind_rows(aug_2024, may_2025)

combined_data_clean <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(
    Export_Value = replace_na(Export_Value, 0),
    Import_Value = replace_na(Import_Value, 0)
  )
ohio_trend_data <- combined_data_clean %>%  
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = Month,
    values_from = c(Export_Value, Import_Value),
    names_glue = "{.value}_{Month}"
  )

ohio_trend_data <- ohio_trend_data %>%
  mutate(
    Export_Change = Export_Value_May2025 - Export_Value_Aug2024,
    Import_Change = Import_Value_May2025 - Import_Value_Aug2024
  )
category_trends <- ohio_trend_data %>%
  group_by(Category) %>%
  summarise(
    Total_Export_Aug2024 = sum(Export_Value_Aug2024, na.rm = TRUE),

    Total_Import_Aug2024 = sum(Import_Value_Aug2024, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Import_May2025 = sum(Import_Value_May2025, na.rm = TRUE),

  arrange(desc(Export_Change))
ggplot(category_trends, aes(x = reorder(Category, Export_Change), y = Export_Change)) +

Observation:

  • Most export categories went down: The majority of product groups (like electronics, vehicles, and chemicals) had lower export values in May 2025 compared to August 2024.

  • Biggest drops: The biggest decreases were in Electronics and electrical machinery, Vehicles, and Chemicals these industries lost the most export value during this time.

  • Other categories had smaller declines: Areas such as agricultural products, base metals, plastics & rubber, textiles, mineral fuels, and instruments/medical goods also saw declines, but these were much smaller.

  • Only Other category grew: The Other category was the only group to show a clear increase in exports, meaning less common or emerging products did better while main sectors fell.

  • China is the second largest importer, with imports slightly less than the USA.

  • Germany is the third largest importer, but with much lower imports than both the USA and China.

  • Japan, United Kingdom, and France occupy the next ranks, each showing progressively lower import values.

  • There is a noticeable gap between the top two countries (USA and China) and all others.

  • The remaining countries (Hong Kong SAR, Netherlands, South Korea, India, Italy, Mexico, Canada, Spain, Singapore) have significantly lower import totals.

# Remove aggregate rows with product code "_T" or "TOTAL" that represent totals rather than specific products
OECD_clean_data <- OECD_clean_data %>%
  filter(!PRODUCT_HS %in% c("_T", "TOTAL"))

OECD_clean_data <- OECD_clean_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(obsValue) & obsValue > 0)

2) Identifying Top Importers by Product Sector in OECD Trade Data

library(dplyr)


OECD_named_data <- OECD_clean_data %>%
  left_join(product_lookup, by = "PRODUCT_HS") %>%
  mutate(PRODUCT_HS = PRODUCT_DESC) %>%
  select(-PRODUCT_DESC)

trade_summary <- OECD_named_data %>%
  group_by(obsTime, COUNTERPART_AREA, PRODUCT_HS) %>%
  summarise(total_export_usd = sum(obsValue, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

country_lookup <- data.frame(
  COUNTERPART_AREA = c("CAN", "MEX", "DEU", "FRA", "CHN", "GBR", "NLD", "JPN", "ESP", "IND"),
  COUNTRY_NAME = c("Canada", "Mexico", "Germany", "France", "China", "United Kingdom", "Netherlands", "Japan", "Spain", "India"),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)

trade_summary_named <- trade_summary %>%
  left_join(country_lookup, by = "COUNTERPART_AREA")

# Find top importers by product
top_importers <- trade_summary_named %>%
  group_by(PRODUCT_HS) %>%
  arrange(desc(total_export_usd)) %>%
  slice(1) %>%
  select(PRODUCT_HS, COUNTRY_NAME, total_export_usd)

Recommendations

U.S. Census

1. We retrieved population and income information for every U.S. state
  • We found that you cannot judge a states income level just by looking at its population. Some smaller states actually have higher average incomes than much larger states.
This can help the app by:

  • Making sure the app does not recommend markets or opportunities based only on population size.

  • Instead, the app can highlight states or regions where people have more income to spend, which means better business opportunities no matter the population size.

2. We extracted information on education levels, unemployment rates, poverty rates, and manufacturing employment for each state.

  • We found that states with higher education rates generally have higher incomes and lower poverty and unemployment.

  • Places with high poverty or unemployment often have lower incomes, even if they have big populations or lots of manufacturing jobs.

  • Manufacturing is important, but by itself, it doesnt guarantee higher incomes the overall education and poverty levels matter more.

This can help the app by:

  • Helping users spot states or regions that are more likely to succeed in trade because they have a skilled, educated population and less poverty

  • Making the apps advice more helpful and practical, because it takes into account the real social and economic background, not just surface numbers.

UN Comtrade

From the UN Comtrade global trade data (20202023)
  • we gathered yearly import and export values for all countries across all commodities.
  • We identified the top 15 countries by total import value, finding that the USA and China lead by a wide margin, followed by countries like Germany, Japan, and the UK.
This can help the app by:

  • The app can highlight the biggest global markets by import volume, showing users where demand is highest worldwide.

  • This allows businesses to prioritize which countries to target for exports based on total import size, improving strategy and focus.

OECD Trade Data

From the OECD Import Data

  • Used filters based on Ohios export profile (such as picking the key countries and products relevant to Ohio) to pull focused export data.

  • This allows us to see how U.S. exports perform in the same markets and product categories where Ohio is active making such analysis more directly useful for Ohios trade interests.

From the OECD Export Data

  • Found that Machinery and Electrical Machinery had the highest export values every year.

  • Pharmaceuticals and Plastics exported less but stayed steady.

  • Trends over these years were mostly stable or slightly increasing, with no dramatic jumps or drops in any product sector.

This can help the app by:
  • The app can let users filter and view import/export data for just the countries and products that matter most to their industry or region (like Ohio).

Regression using Census data

  • We collected U.S. Census data for each state, including: population, education rate (percent with bachelors degree or higher), unemployment rate, poverty rate, share of manufacturing jobs, and median household income.

  • We randomly split this set into a training group (to build our model) and a test group (to see how well the model works on new, unseen states).

The results showed:
  • Education rate: States with more educated people tend to have much higher incomes.
  • Poverty rate: More poverty means much lower incomes.
  • Population and manufacturing: These didnt actually help predict income very well.
This can help the app by:
  • Businesses using the app can choose the best states or markets to focus on by looking at where people are well-educated and poverty is low, instead of just guessing based on how big the population or industry is.
